For example, when typing: 
{noformat}
* Bullet 1
{noformat}
followed by <Enter>, JIRA will automatically insert "* " at the start of the next line so you can start typing Bullet 2. 

However, this does not work for sub-bullets. When typing:
{noformat}
* Bullet 1
** Sub-bullet 1
{noformat}
followed by <Enter>, JIRA should should insert "** " at the start of the next line so you can start typing Sub-bullet 2. This change should affect numbered lists.

The services don't works. The services do not start.

We found a bug in  com.atlassian.jira.service.DefaultServiceManager:

{code:title=DefaultServiceManager.java|borderStyle=solid}
private void scheduleJob(final JiraServiceContainer jiraServiceContainer, final boolean notify) throws SchedulerServiceException
    {
        if (jiraServiceContainer.getDelay() <= 0)
        {
            return;
        }
        // Work out the fire time delay.
        Date nextFireTime = null;
        long lastRunMillis = jiraServiceContainer.getLastRun();
        final long nextRunMillis =
                lastRunMillis > 0 ? lastRunMillis + jiraServiceContainer.getDelay() : System.currentTimeMillis();
        final boolean localService = jiraServiceContainer.isLocalService();
 
        if (nextRunMillis > System.currentTimeMillis())
        {
            nextFireTime = new Date(nextRunMillis);
        }
        JobConfig config = JobConfig.forJobRunnerKey(SERVICE_JOB_KEY)
                .withSchedule(Schedule.forInterval(jiraServiceContainer.getDelay(), nextFireTime))
                .withRunMode(localService ? RunMode.RUN_LOCALLY : RunMode.RUN_ONCE_PER_CLUSTER)
                .withParameters(ImmutableMap.<String, Serializable>of(SERVICE_ID_KEY, jiraServiceContainer.getId()));
 
        schedulerService.scheduleJob(toJobId(jiraServiceContainer.getId()), config);
 
        if (localService && notify)
        {
            messagingService.sendRemote(RESCHEDULE_SERVICE, jiraServiceContainer.getId().toString());
        }
    }
{code}

Pay attention on this line:
{code:title=DefaultServiceManager.java|borderStyle=solid}
final long nextRunMillis =
                lastRunMillis > 0 ? lastRunMillis + jiraServiceContainer.getDelay() : System.currentTimeMillis();
 {code}


For any just created jira service lastRunMillis is 0. So we will have System.currentTimeMillis() in nextRunMillis.
 
Few lines later (and that also means “few moments later”) we have this lines of code:
{code:title=DefaultServiceManager.java|borderStyle=solid}
        if (nextRunMillis > System.currentTimeMillis())
        {
            nextFireTime = new Date(nextRunMillis);
        }
{code}

Cause of the upper arguments, for any just created jira service condition will be false.
So, nextFireTime for created services is always null.
 
So, any time we registering new service we do it with null next run time => incorrect.
